comments.text:
Hi @deshbhakt! Love the kind of content you make. That said, I am going to post this comment on multiple videos of yours so that the odds of you seeing it increase, given that your videos generate numerous comments and therefore, there is a huge chance of this being lost. This comment includes a heartfelt request.

The budget this year was terrible and one of the reasons given was that the government is low on funds. Which leads me to my point. Parliamentarians and Legislative Assembly members, even if they have served just one term, are entitled to a pension for their entire lives. That money comes from the pockets of taxpayers like us. In addition to that, any other benefits that ex-MPs and ex-MLAs may receive. So, given your strength of research, can you please make an episode on how much it costs us per year, as middle-class citizens to sustain those pensions? Also, if you can add the cost of subsidy that we have to bear for the food served in the Parliament canteen and how much loss is it leading to? Is it possible that if these pensions are halted or the rule is changed to Parliamentarians with at least 4 terms being eligible, will it be better? After all, even soldiers who put their life on the line for the country have to serve for 20 years before being eligible for pension. So why the exception for politicians? In any case, other government employees don't have their pension anyway! If we know what kind of money we can save as a country without these pensions, hopefully, we will have a better budget next year.

Cheers!
